/*
Each ball has the following things:

	- a kind, which is the `Kind` in `ball Kind {};`.
	- some balls it is bound to, eg 
	  `ball Kind { ...  next: SomeKind; ...};`
	- kinds can match multiple kinds, like 
	  `{ ... next: SomeKind | OtherKind; ... }`.
	- some actions.

Each ball may have a list of actions, which it starts executing at the top
and goes action by action.

Note that eventually taking actions will require some kind of energy or the
like, plus material as well, so that balls will need to be larger, made of
more material, to be able to have more  actions in its definition.

Actions:

`some_bond = some_ball`
Bind a ball to a bond slot. If the other_ball is not very close, first swim
to it to touch it, then bind it. Bonds are directed, it might very well be that
a ball binds another ball, while the other ball does not bind the first
ball. Can be one's own bond or some_other_ball.bond (where some other ball
might be specified through a chain of bonds as well of course).

`some_bond = release`
Release a bond if it was bound.

`some_state = NewState`
Change state. Can be state for the ball's own state or some_ball.state for
some other ball.

`some_kind = NewKind`
Change kind. Can be kind for the ball's own kind, or some_ball.kind for some
other ball.

`label:`
The definition a label.

`go label`
Continue at label.

`sleep time`
Wait a bit.

`if (condition) action`
A conditional action. Condition can be equality of kind for example.

Balls are specified either just by kind, in which case it finds a nearby
such ball, or by a bond or chain of bonds (like original or original.next).

Whenever non-existing balls are referenced, or incorrect types are bound in
a bond, we log those but let the simulation keep on running.

Balls can also inherit from another ball and modify the inherited behavior.

Scenarios are defined by listing ball kinds. Whenever a kind is referenced,
a new such ball is created.

*/

/*
A generic material to be converted into useful stuff.
*/
ball Blank {};

/*
========================
Information chain balls.
========================
*/
ball Chain {};

/*
The first ball of the chain, does not carry information.
*/
ball Cap: Chain {
	next: Info;
};

/*
An information carrier in the middle of the chain.
*/
ball Info: Chain {
	next: Info | End;
	prev: Cap | Info;
};

/*
Different kinds of information. These could be side chains as well, for
simplicity, they are different balls now.
*/
ball Info_1 : Info {};
ball Info_2 : Info {};
ball Info_3 : Info {};

/* 
A terminating ball, carrying no information.
*/
ball End: Chain {
	prev: Info;
};

/*
====================
A simple polymerase.
====================
*/
ball Polymerase {
	original: Chain;
	material: Blank;
	copy: Chain;

	{
		start:
		original = Cap;
		material = Blank;
		material.kind = original.kind;
		copy = material;
		
		clone:
		original = original.next;
		material = Blank;
		material.kind = original.kind;
		copy.next = material;
		material.prev = copy;
		copy = material;
		if (copy.kind != End) go clone;
		
		original = release;
		material = release;
		copy = release;
		go start;
	}
};

/*
====================
A simple monomerase.
====================
*/
ball Monomerase {
	bond chain: End;
	bond prev: Chain;

	{
		start:
		chain = End;

		split:
		prev = chain.prev;
		chain.prev = release;
		prev.next = release;
		chain = prev;
		if (chain.kind != Cap) go split;

		chain = release;
		prev = release;
		sleep 5s;
		go start;
	}
};

/*
A simple test scenario.
*/
scenario Test {
	Blank * 1000;
	Polymerase;
	chain = Cap;
	chain.next = Info_1;
	chain = chain.next;
	chain.next = Info_2;
	chain = chain.next;
	chain.next = Info_3;
	chain = chain.next;
	chain = End;
};
